title: Magna Carta Signed
description: King John of England signed the Magna Carta, establishing the principle that everyone is subject to the law, including the king.

title: Gutenberg's Printing Press
description: Johannes Gutenberg invented the printing press with movable type, revolutionizing the spread of information.

title: Columbus Reaches the Americas
description: Christopher Columbus made his first landfall in the Americas, beginning European exploration of the New World.

title: Hamlet First Performance
description: William Shakespeare's tragedy Hamlet was first performed, becoming one of the greatest works in English literature.

title: First Telescope Invented
description: Hans Lippershey created the first practical telescope, revolutionizing astronomy and navigation.

title: Boston Tea Party
description: American colonists dumped British tea into Boston Harbor in protest of taxation without representation.

title: Watt's Steam Engine Patent
description: James Watt patented his improved steam engine, sparking the Industrial Revolution.

title: French Revolution Begins
description: The storming of the Bastille marked the beginning of the French Revolution.

title: Battle of Waterloo
description: Napoleon Bonaparte was defeated at Waterloo, ending his rule and the Napoleonic Wars.

title: Photography Invented
description: Louis Daguerre announced the daguerreotype process, making photography available to the public.

title: First Telegraph Message
description: Samuel Morse sent the first long-distance telegraph message: 'What hath God wrought'.

title: American Civil War Begins
description: Confederate forces fired on Fort Sumter, beginning the American Civil War.

title: First Telephone Call
description: Alexander Graham Bell made the first successful telephone call to his assistant.

title: Edison's Light Bulb
description: Thomas Edison successfully tested his incandescent light bulb, lighting up the modern world.

title: First Powered Flight
description: The Wright brothers achieved the first powered, sustained, and controlled heavier-than-air human flight.

title: Einstein's Theory of Relativity
description: Albert Einstein published his special theory of relativity, revolutionizing physics.

title: Titanic Sinks
description: The RMS Titanic sank on its maiden voyage after hitting an iceberg, killing over 1,500 people.

title: World War I Begins
description: Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia, beginning World War I.

title: Discovery of Penicillin
description: Alexander Fleming discovered penicillin, revolutionizing medicine and saving millions of lives.

title: Stock Market Crash
description: Black Tuesday marked the beginning of the Great Depression.

title: World War II Begins
description: Germany invaded Poland, beginning World War II in Europe.

title: Dunkirk Evacuation
description: The evacuation of Allied soldiers during World War II from the beaches and harbour of Dunkirk, in the north of France, between 26 May and 4 June 1940.

title: Battle of Britain
description: A military campaign of the Second World War, in which the Royal Air Force (RAF) defended the United Kingdom against large-scale attacks by Nazi Germany's air force, the Luftwaffe.

title: Lend-Lease Act Signed
description: President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed the Lend-Lease Act, providing U.S. military aid to foreign nations during World War II.

title: Operation Barbarossa Begins
description: The code name for the Axis invasion of the Soviet Union, starting the war on the Eastern Front.

title: Atlantic Charter Issued
description: A pivotal policy statement issued by Winston Churchill and Franklin D. Roosevelt that defined the Allied goals for the post-war world.

title: Siege of Leningrad Begins
description: The prolonged military blockade of Leningrad by German, Finnish, and Spanish Blue Division forces during World War II. The siege was one of the longest and most destructive in history.

title: Battle of Moscow Begins
description: A military campaign that consisted of two periods of strategically significant fighting on a 600 km sector of the Eastern Front during World War II. The Soviet defensive effort frustrated Hitler's attack on Moscow.

title: Attack on Pearl Harbor
description: The Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service launched a surprise military strike against the United States naval base at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii Territory, leading to the United States' formal entry into World War II the next day.

title: Battle of Midway
description: A decisive naval battle in the Pacific Theater of World War II which occurred six months after Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor and was a crucial turning point.

title: Battle of Stalingrad
description: A major confrontation of World War II in which Nazi Germany and its allies fought the Soviet Union for control of the city of Stalingrad in Southern Russia. It was a turning point on the Eastern Front.

title: Warsaw Ghetto Uprising
description: The 1943 act of Jewish resistance in the Warsaw Ghetto in German-occupied Poland to oppose Nazi Germany's final effort to transport the remaining ghetto population to extermination camps.

title: D-Day: Normandy Landings
description: The Allied invasion of Normandy in Operation Overlord during World War II. The largest seaborne invasion in history, it began the liberation of France and Western Europe.

title: Battle of the Bulge
description: The last major German offensive campaign on the Western Front during World War II.

title: Yalta Conference
description: A meeting of the heads of government of the United States, the United Kingdom, and the Soviet Union to discuss the postwar reorganization of Germany and Europe.

title: Victory in Europe Day (VE Day)
description: The formal acceptance by the Allies of World War II of Nazi Germany's unconditional surrender of its armed forces, marking the end of World War II in Europe.

title: Atomic Bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki
description: The United States detonated two nuclear weapons over the Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, leading to Japan's surrender and the end of World War II.

title: DNA Structure Discovered
description: Watson and Crick published the double helix structure of DNA.

title: Construction of Berlin Wall
description: East German authorities began construction of the Berlin Wall, dividing East and West Berlin during the Cold War.

title: Cuban Missile Crisis
description: A 13-day political and military standoff between the United States and Soviet Union over nuclear missiles in Cuba.

title: Assassination of John F. Kennedy
description: The 35th President of the United States was assassinated while riding in a presidential motorcade in Dallas.

title: The Beatles on The Ed Sullivan Show
description: The Beatles made their American television debut, sparking Beatlemania across the United States.

title: First Computer Mouse Demonstration
description: Douglas Engelbart demonstrated the first computer mouse, revolutionizing human-computer interaction.

title: Selma to Montgomery Marches
description: A series of civil rights marches led by Martin Luther King Jr. for African American voting rights.

title: 1966 FIFA World Cup Final
description: England defeated West Germany 4-2 to win their first and only FIFA World Cup.

title: Apollo 11 Moon Landing
description: The first manned moon landing mission, with Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin becoming the first humans to walk on the lunar surface.

title: Woodstock Music Festival

title: First ARPANET Connection

title: IBM Personal Computer Released

title: Fall of the Berlin Wall

title: World Wide Web Goes Public
